# Public Prosecutor _v_ Gary Choo Pu Chang  

### \[2022\] SGDC 128

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Summons Case No 900162 of 2019, Magistrate's Appeal No MA-9092-2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">10 June 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Melissa Tan</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Samuel Chua and Khong Zi-Wei (Ministry of Manpower) for the Public Prosecutor; Ong Lian-Yi Gregory (David Ong &amp; Co, Advocates &amp; Solicitors) for the Accused.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Gary Choo Pu Chang</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Law – Statutory Offences – Workplace Safety and Health Act

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9092/2022/01.\]

10 June 2022

### District Judge Melissa Tan:

## Introduction

1       The Accused is a 64-year-old male Singapore citizen. He was the Executive Director of Leeden National Oxygen Ltd (“LNOX”) between 1 October 2014 and 12 August 2015.

2       The Accused initially claimed trial before another court. After the first tranche of trial, he pleaded guilty to an amended charge under s 12(1) read with s 20 and s 48(1) of the Workplace Safety and Health Act (Cap 354A, 2009 Rev Ed) (“WSHA”) punishable under s 50(_a_) of the WSHA for failing to take such measures as were necessary to ensure the safety and health of LNOX’s employees who were working in its laboratory in the Specialty Gas Centre (“the laboratory”) located at 21 Tanjong Kling Road, Singapore 628047. The laboratory was a workplace within the meaning of the WSHA.

3       The charge stated that between 1 October 2014 and 12 August 2015, LNOX had:

> (a)     failed to take reasonably practicable measures to ensure that unsafe modified regulatory valve assemblies (“RVAs”) were not used in the laboratory when testing combustible gases;

> (b)     failed to ensure that there was a system for the tracking and maintenance of the RVAs used in the laboratory;

> (c)     failed to ensure that an adequate risk assessment was conducted in respect of the operations of the laboratory as required under Regulation 3 of the Workplace Safety and Health (Risk Management) Regulations (“the Regulations”);

> (d)     failed to establish adequate safe work procedures for the gas analysis work conducted in the laboratory as required under Regulation 4 of the Regulations;

> (e)     failed to ensure that there was a system in place for the accurate tracking of gas cylinders; and

> (f)     failed to ensure that safety concerns raised in relation to the proposal to change the gas detection system at the workplace were addressed.

4       The charge further stated that the Accused was the Executive Director of LNOX whose responsibilities included exercising management oversight of the safe operation of the laboratory.

5       The Accused was sentenced to a fine of $45,000 (in default two months’ imprisonment). I granted the Accused’s application for time to pay the fine. He has paid the fine in full.

6       Being dissatisfied, the Accused lodged an appeal against his sentence.

## Facts

7       The Prosecution submitted a detailed and lengthy Statement of Facts that the Accused admitted to without qualification. The salient facts are summarised below.

### Background

8       LNOX was engaged in the business of selling, producing, and distributing industrial and specialty gases. It was established on 1 October 2014, following the merger of Leeden Ltd and National Oxygen Pte Ltd (“NOPL”).

9       Between 1 October 2014 and 12 August 2015, the Accused was employed by LNOX. Prior to the merger, the Accused was NOPL’s Deputy Managing Director. His responsibilities included overseeing several departments, including the laboratory. Following the merger, NOPL was absorbed into LNOX. The Accused was appointed LNOX’s Executive Director. He continued to oversee several departments, including the laboratory. Upon his resignation on 12 August 2015, LNOX’s Managing Director-cum-Chief Operations Officer, Mr Kelvin Lee Chee Fatt (“Mr Kelvin Lee”), assumed the Accused’s portfolio. Both LNOX and Mr Kelvin Lee maintained the status quo of all operations and safety-related procedures in the laboratory and did not undertake any reviews of the laboratory’s safety procedures.

10     The laboratory was known as the Quality Control Laboratory. It carried out analysis of gases contained in gas cylinders of various capacities and pressures, as well as verified whether the gases met LNOX’s customers’ requirements before delivery.

### The Accident

11     On 12 October 2015, at about 9.20am, an explosion occurred at the laboratory, followed by a series of fire explosions. At the material time, a chemist working at the laboratory, Ms Lim Siaw Chian (“the Deceased”), was carrying out gas analysis on a gas cylinder.

12     The initial explosion caused her death and injured three others who were working in the laboratory. Another four LNOX employees sustained injuries.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) The cause of the Deceased’s death was certified as “Blast Injuries”. A Coroner’s Inquiry found that the death was due to an industrial misadventure.

### Investigations

13     The CCTV footage of the laboratory showed that the initial explosion took place towards the rear of the laboratory. The Deceased was captured touching a regulatory valve assembly (“the incident RVA”) that was connected to a gas cylinder (“the incident cylinder”) beside a gas chromatography machine (“the incident GCM”). Thereafter, a bright light was seen, and the CCTV footage went blank.

14     A forensic report was prepared by MATCOR Technology & Services Pte Ltd. The report stated that the Deceased attached the incident cylinder to the incident GCM using the incident RVA. At the time, the incident cylinder contained a combustible mixture of methane, nitrogen and oxygen (“the gaseous mixture”). In summary, the findings from the forensic engineering assessment were as follows:

> (a)     The primary failure was located at an unqualified welded joint found in the bullet stem of the incident RVA, which was attached to the cylinder valve of the incident gas cylinder.

> (b)     The incident RVA was supposed to be British Standard (BS) 341 No. 4 type with a bullet stem free of welded joint. However, the incident RVA was modified with an unqualified welded joint. Any RVAs with welded components should not be used, unless qualified and approved by the manufacturer.

> (c)     The failure of the welded joint was found to have pre-existed. It was not prudently checked before usage prior to the incident. Damage caused by fatigue propagation grew over time during usage.

> (d)     When the Deceased made contact with the valve, the welded joint was on the verge of failure and leakage. When the gaseous mixture leaked, the spontaneous reaction of the gaseous mixture in the presence of frictional heat generated led to an ignition.

> (e)     The ignition reaction led to an explosion inside the cylinder, which led to a voluminous pressure build-up and overload rupture of the cylinder.

> (f)     The accident could have been prevented if there was consistent prudent maintenance or inspection of the RVAs before and after every testing conducted by the personnel.

15     The following diagrams are sectional drawings showing connections with a modified RVA and an unmodified RVA respectively:

16     Investigations revealed a series of LNOX’s failures.

#### Failure to take reasonably practicable measures to ensure that unsafe modified RVAs were not used in the laboratory when testing combustible gases

17     The Deceased was testing a cylinder that contained the gaseous mixture. She attached the incident cylinder to the incident GCM using the incident RVA that was found to have been modified with an unqualified welded joint. Any welded RVAs should not have been used unless qualified and approved by a manufacturer.

18     Apart from the modified RVA that the Deceased used, some of the RVAs recovered from the laboratory were also found to be modified.

#### Failure to ensure that there was a system for the tracking and maintenance of the RVAs used in the laboratory

19     While the Accused was overseeing the departments, including the laboratory, first as NOPL’s Deputy Managing Director and subsequently as LNOX’s Executive Director, LNOX regarded RVAs as consumables and purchased them in bulk from various suppliers. LNOX did not keep or maintain any records of when the purchases were made, which suppliers they were purchased from, which RVAs were modified, and whether the modified RVAs had been qualified and approved by the manufacturer. As such, LNOX was unable to trace which suppliers had provided them with the modified RVAs.

20     There was no system for the tracking and maintenance of the RVAs in the laboratory. All RVAs, including the incident RVA, were randomly kept in a toolbox cabinet in the laboratory. They were not individually tracked for their date and source of purchase, physical integrity and suitability for continued use. Besides leak tests conducted on the connectors of the RVAs after purchase, there was no periodic testing or maintenance of the RVAs.

#### Failure to ensure that an adequate risk assessment was conducted in respect of the operations of the laboratory

21     Regulation 3 of the Regulations provides that an employer shall conduct a risk assessment in relation to the safety and health risks posed to any person who may be affected by his undertaking in the workplace. Regulation 4 of the Regulations provides that the employer shall take all reasonably practicable steps to eliminate any foreseeable risk to any person who may be affected by his undertaking in the workplace. Where it is not reasonably practicable to do so, the employer shall implement reasonably practicable measures to minimise the risk and safe work procedures to control the risk.

22     Under the Code of Practice on Workplace Safety and Health Risk Management (“Code of Practice”), the Accused’s responsibilities as an “Employer” included, among other things, ensuring that a risk assessment was conducted on workplace safety and health risks associated with activities in the laboratory, taking reasonably practicable steps to eliminate foreseeable risks and taking measures to control the risks.

23     On 7 November 2011, a risk assessment was conducted for the analysis of flammable gases by the head of the Specialty Gas Centre and a Senior Quality Manager at the laboratory, Mr Kumpang Anak Endawi.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) The risk assessment identified four work activities. With respect to the activity of introducing samples into the analyser, the risk assessment identified three hazards, namely, sample leak, fire and explosion, and proposed the various risk control measures, including snoop leak check and oxygen/flammable gas detector.

24     After LNOX was established on 1 October 2014, there was no review of the risk assessment.

25     Investigations revealed that the risk assessment conducted was perfunctory, simplistic and inadequate. The work activities for which risk assessment was necessary ought to have included the temporary placement of gas cylinders in the laboratory for the purpose of sample-testing their contents. The risk control measures ought to have included measures such as the proper tracking of the RVAs, the proper identification and labelling of the RVAs, the segregation of the RVAs based on their types and the type of gas they were used to test, the inspection of RVAs for modifications and the immediate isolation and discarding of modified RVAs, and the temporary safe placement of gas cylinders in the laboratory before analysis and timely removal after analysis.

26     Where there was a lack of experience in risk assessment, LNOX should have engaged a workplace safety and health officer, workplace safety and health auditor or approved third-party consultant to assist LNOX’s risk assessment team in conducting the risk assessment.

#### Failure to establish adequate safe work procedures for the gas analysis work conducted in the laboratory

27     Arising from the risk assessment, safe work procedures should have been established and implemented to control the risks that cannot be fully eliminated.

28     However, LNOX had not established any safe work procedures for the gas analysis process in the laboratory. Although there were generic work instructions for gas analysis, there were no systemic instructions for the safe operation of gas analysis.

#### Failure to ensure that there was a system in place for the accurate tracking of gas cylinders

29     Even though LNOX was not licensed to store petroleum and flammable material in the laboratory, cylinders of combustible gases were stored there for easy access and retrieval during calibration or gas analysis.

30     LNOX did not have an adequate system to record, trace, validate and identify the actual number, content, nature and location of the gas cylinders that were moved in and out of the laboratory, as well as the status of the gas cylinders requiring gas analysis. After the accident, LNOX was unable to accurately furnish the actual number, capacity, content, nature, pressure and location of the gas cylinders that were stored in the laboratory.

#### Failure to ensure that safety concerns raised in relation to the proposal to change the gas detection system at workplace were addressed

31     Sometime in October 2014, the Safety Manager, Mr Lee Mun Hong, discovered during a routine inspection that the gas leakage indication lights of the gas detection system were blinking occasionally without any obvious triggers. This meant that the gas detection system was not reliable in the event of an actual gas leak.

32     Sometime before or in May 2015, Mr Lee Mun Hong received a quotation from a contractor for his proposal to revamp LNOX’s gas detection system. Although he showed the proposal to the Accused, the Accused informed him that LNOX did not have the budget to perform such work and that he should push the proposal to the next year. The explosion took place before the next year’s budget proposal.

### The Accused’s Responsibilities

33     As the Executive Director of LNOX between 1 October 2014 and 12 August 2015, the Accused’s responsibilities included exercising management oversight of the safe operation of the laboratory. Having regard to the nature of his functions in that capacity and to all the circumstances, he failed to exercise all such diligence to prevent LNOX’s commission of the offence under s 12(1) of the WSHA, as he ought to have exercised.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalty

34     Section 50(_a_) of the WSHA states that in the case of a natural person, the prescribed penalty is a fine not exceeding $200,000 or imprisonment not exceeding 2 years or both.

### Antecedents

35     The Accused was untraced.

### Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

36     The Prosecution sought a fine of between $45,000 and $60,000.

37     The Prosecution submitted that general deterrence was the overarching sentencing consideration for offences under the WSHA. While the Prosecution noted that there was no sentencing framework for an offence under s 12(1) of the WSHA committed by a natural person, the Prosecution relied on the sentencing factors identified by the High Court in _Mao Xuezhong v Public Prosecutor and another appeal_ <span class="citation"></span><span class="citation">\[2020\] 5 SLR 580</span> (“_Mao Xuezhong_”) and _Public Prosecutor v GS Engineering & Construction Corp_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 3 SLR 682</span> (“_GS Engineering_”) (particularly \[77(d)\]).

38     The Prosecution highlighted the following sentencing factors:

> (a)     There was serious harm risked. The laboratory operations included siphoning flammable gases from large cylinders of pressurised gases in an oxygen-enriched environment. The potential for explosions and fires was very real, and the foreseeable outcome of such explosions and fires would have been serious injury or even death (which resulted in this case).

> (b)     The likelihood of the harm was high. The siphoning and testing of flammable gases were part of the daily responsibilities of the chemists and technicians working in the laboratory. There would therefore have been a constant potential for explosions and fires to occur.

> (c)     The number of personnel likely to be exposed to the risk of harm was not insignificant. This composed of the chemists and technicians working in the laboratory. On the date of the accident, there were four of them present.

> (d)     Although the Accused pleaded guilty, he did so belatedly after the first tranche of trial concluded and after the Prosecution expended significant time and manpower resources to prepare for trial. Any mitigating value on his guilty plea should be lesser than if he pleaded guilty at an earlier stage. There were no other mitigating factors.

39     The Prosecution also referred to unreported cases as sentencing precedents, which I will discuss at \[60\] below. While recognising that they were of limited precedential value, the Prosecution submitted that they served as useful reference points on the sentences typically imposed in similar factual scenarios. In particular, the Prosecution submitted that the case involving LNOX’s Chief Executive Officer (“CEO”), _Public Prosecutor v Tham Weng Cheong, Steven_ (SC-903581-2019) was the most relevant.

40     The Prosecution also contended that although actual harm did not take place during the Accused’s tenure, the potential for harm was always present. In fact, there were no changes in operational procedures in the laboratory after the Accused resigned. It was only fortuitous that the harm did not materialise only until after the Accused’s resignation.

### Mitigation & Defence’s Submissions on Sentence

41     The Defence sought a fine of between $30,000 and $40,000.

42     The Defence submitted that the applicable guidelines for determining the appropriate sentence are set out in _GS Engineering_ at \[77\], which were approved in _MW Group Pte Ltd v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGHC 5</span> (“_MW Group_”).

43     In terms of culpability, the Defence submitted that it was in the low to medium range for the following reasons:

> (a)     The laboratory was one of the departments that the Accused was in-charge of and had management oversight. However, as he was not qualified in gas analysis and there were other more qualified and experienced people dedicated and/or working in the laboratory on a day-to-day operational basis, his culpability could be of a lower level in that he could have exercised a degree of due diligence and take necessary reasonably practicable measures from 1 October 2014 to 12 July 2015 (_ie_, the date when he tendered his notice of resignation).

> (b)     There was an environmental health and safety system and process (“EHS Structure”) within LNOX. The Accused was not part of the personnel responsible for implementing the safety matters or risk management and safety procedures in relation to the laboratory or other department of LNOX. Neither was he involved in the external audit of LNOX’s safety and safe work procedures.

> (c)     The concluding paragraph in the charge against LNOX’s CEO, Mr Tham stated that the particulars of unsafe transgressions caused the death of the Deceased whereas the concluding paragraph in the amended charge against the Accused stated that he had management oversight of the safe operation of the laboratory. The difference in the wording of the charges recognised that the ultimate responsibility for unsafe practices laid with the CEO. This position is also affirmed in the Quality Environmental Health and Safety Manual (“EHS Manual”).

44     The Defence argued that there were no aggravating factors and urged the Court to consider the following mitigating factors:

> (a)     No similar explosion took place prior to the explosion on 12 October 2015. It was an isolated incident.

> (b)     The explosion occurred after he physically left the employment of LNOX. Mr Kelvin Lee had simply maintained the status quo of all operations. Neither LNOX nor Mr Kelvin Lee asked the Accused to undergo a proper handover of operations and safety related procedures.

> (c)     The Accused is a first-time offender.

> (d)     With regard to his plea of guilt, the Accused was offered the amended charge under s 12(1) of the WSHA on 7 February 2022, after two days of trial. He accepted the offer in a timely manner on 28 February 2022.

> (e)     The Accused cooperated with the authorities in investigations.

45     In addition, the Defence tendered a list of offenders convicted under s 12(1) of the WSHA and the fines imposed in those cases. The Defence stated that the list was obtained from the Ministry of Manpower’s website.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)

### Decision on Sentence

#### Applicable principles

46     The primary sentencing consideration in this case is general deterrence. As the High Court in _GS Engineering_ observed (at \[51\]):

> It is discernible from the above extracts that the introduction of more severe penalties for such offences in the WSHA was part of a concerted effort to deter poor safety management and effect a cultural change for employers and other stakeholders to take proactive measures to prevent accidents at the workplace. The necessary implication is that _Parliament’s intention was for the courts to impose higher penalties, where appropriate, in order to achieve such a deterrent effect_ and ensure that the true economic and social costs of such risks and accidents are borne by the responsible parties.

> \[emphasis added\]

47     In my view, _GS Engineering_ and _MW Group_ are instructive in setting out the approach that this court should take in determining the appropriate sentence. Both cases similarly involved offences under s 12(1) read with s 20(1) of the WSHA.

48     I will now briefly outline the approach laid down in _GS Engineering_ and _MW Group_. In _GS Engineering_, See Kee Oon JC (as he then was) adopted the following two-step sentencing framework (at \[77\]):

> (a)     At the first step, the court should determine the appropriate starting point from a set of sentencing ranges (see \[70\] of _GS Engineering_) by considering the culpability of the offender and the harm that could potentially have resulted. The culpability of the offender may depend on the following non-exhaustive list of factors: (i) the number of breaches or failures; (ii) the nature of the breaches; (iii) the seriousness of the breaches – whether they were a minor departure from the established procedure or whether they were a complete disregard of the procedures; (iv) whether the breaches were systemic or whether they were part of an isolated incident; and (v) whether the breaches were intentional, rash or negligent. The potential harm may be assessed by considering factors such as the seriousness of the harm risked and the likelihood of that harm arising.

> (b)     At the second step, the court should calibrate the sentence by considering the aggravating and mitigating factors of the case. Aggravating factors included: (i) serious actual harm (including death) resulted; (ii) the breach was a significant cause of the harm that resulted; (iii) the offender had cut cost at the expense of the safety of the workers; (iv) there was deliberate concealment of the illegal nature of the activity; (v) there was a breach of a court order; (vi) there was an obstruction of justice; (vii) the offender has a poor workplace health and safety record; (viii) there was a deliberate falsification of documentation or licences; and (ix) there was a deliberate failure to obtain or comply with relevant licences in order to avoid the authorities’ scrutiny. Mitigating factors included: (i) the offender had voluntarily taken steps to remedy the problem; (ii) the offender provided a higher level of cooperation with the authorities for the investigations than normally expected; (iii) there is self-reporting, cooperation and acceptance of responsibility; (iv) there is a timely plea of guilt; (v) the offender has a good health and safety record; (v) the offender has effective health and safety procedures in place.

49     In _MW Group_, Chan Seng Onn J expressed his broad agreement with the sentencing framework adopted in _GS Engineering_ (at \[26\]). He endorsed the non-exhaustive factors for assessing culpability and the level of potential harm, save that he included an additional factor for assessing the level of potential harm, namely, the number of people likely to be exposed to the risk of that harm (at \[27\] – \[28\]). Chan J departed from the decision in _GS Engineering_ in terms of the applicable sentencing ranges (at \[29\]).

50     At this juncture, it is worth highlighting two preliminary points.

51     First, _GS Engineering_ and _MW Group_ involved offences that were committed by companies (as opposed to natural persons) for which the prescribed penalty under s 50(_b_) of the WSHA is a maximum fine of $500,000. As stated at \[34\] above, the prescribed penalty for an offence committed by a natural person, as in the present case, is a lower maximum fine of $200,000 or a maximum of two years’ imprisonment or both. Accordingly, the sentencing ranges laid down in either _GS Engineering_ or _MW Group_ were, in my view, not applicable.

52     Second, as the Prosecution alluded in submissions, a similar set of sentencing factors was more recently considered by the three-judge High Court in _Mao Xuezhong v Public Prosecutor and another appeal_ <span class="citation"></span><span class="citation">\[2020\] 5 SLR 580</span> (“_Mao Xuezhong_”) (at \[64(a)(i)\] – \[64(a)(ii)\]). Unlike in _GS Engineering_ and _MW Group_, the High Court in _Mao Xuezhong_ held that the assessment of the level of harm included a consideration of the degree of both potential harm and actual harm caused (at \[64(a)(i)\]). The case of _Mao Xuezhong_ concerned an offence under a different provision of WSHA, namely, s 15(3A) for performing a negligent act which endangered the safety of others without reasonable excuse. I further noted that the High Court in _Mao Xuezhong_ did not overrule _GS Engineering_ or _MW Group_.

#### Application to present case

##### (1)   Level of culpability

53     I started by assessing the Accused to be of the lower end of medium level of culpability. At the outset, I noted that Mr Choo tendered his notice of resignation, and his last working day at LNOX was on 27 July 2015. This was not disputed by the Prosecution. Be that as it may, LNOX had six failures, which were mostly isolated to the laboratory operations. At all material times, his responsibilities included exercising management oversight of the safe operation of the laboratory.

54     I further noted that the Accused was directly involved in the failure to ensure that safety concerns raised in relation to the proposal to change the gas detection system at the workplace were addressed. Even though the Safety Manager Mr Lee Mun Hong showed the proposal to revamp LNOX’s gas detection system to the Accused, the Accused declined to address the issue owing to the lack of budget (see \[31\] and \[32\] above). The Defence appeared to rely on the audit report dated 24 April 2015.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) In this connection, the Defence submitted that there were no adverse findings in the audit report. The audit report stated that “\[m\]onitoring and measurement process for gas alarm system is in-placed and tests were undertaken by RK Instruments (S) Pte Ltd”.[^5] Even if I accepted the findings of the audit report, I did not think that this helped the Defence’s case because the audit was conducted on 23 and 24 April 2015[^6] whereas Mr Lee Mun Hong approached the Accused after he received the quotation in support of his proposal sometime before or in May 2015. In other words, even if the issues with the gas detection system were not observed by the external auditors, these issues were raised directly to the Accused’s attention.

##### (2)   Level of potential harm

55     I next turned to consider the level of potential harm. In my view, it was of a high level. I agreed with the Prosecution’s submissions that there was serious harm risked. As there were large cylinders of combustible gases in the laboratory, there was a high potential for explosions and fires, which could have led to injuries and even death. The fact that actual death of the Deceased was caused fortified my assessment. The likelihood of the harm was also high given the nature of the laboratory’s work, which entailed activities such as the testing of combustible gases. The number of personnel likely to be exposed would have included all personnel working in the laboratory and even its vicinity.

##### (3)   Aggravating and mitigating factors

56     In my view, there were two aggravating factors. First, serious actual harm eventually materialised in October 2015 when the explosion took place and led to the death of one employee and injuries of seven others. Second, according to the forensic engineering assessment, the breaches in relation to the RVAs were found to have led to the explosion incident. The laboratory had failed to track and maintain the RVAs used in the laboratory before and after the merger. It was purely fortuitous that no similar incidents took place during the time when the Accused was still employed by LNOX.

57     I accorded some mitigating weight in view of the fact that the Accused elected to plead guilty not long after the Prosecution offered to amend the charge. I did not consider that the Accused provided such a high level of cooperation with the authorities for the investigations that mitigating weight should be given. There were, in my view, no other relevant mitigating factors.

#### Sentencing precedents

58     In determining the appropriate sentence, I also considered the precedents cited by the parties.

59     The Prosecution cited five unreported cases. I was mindful that unreported cases are of limited weight in precedential value because they are unreasoned, but they can be helpful in sketching a broad view of relevant sentencing trends (_Tang Ling Lee v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 813</span> at \[22\]).

60     The unreported cases are summarised as follows:

> (a)      _Public Prosecutor v Tham Weng Cheong, Steven_ (DSC-900161-2019) (“_Steven Tham_”): As the CEO of LNOX, Mr Tham was responsible for the overall operations, including safety, human resources and finances. Mr Tham pleaded guilty to a charge under s 12(1) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA for essentially the same set of LNOX’s failures specified in the Accused’s charge, save that Mr Tham’s charge also included the failure to provide adequate support and direction to the employees in respect of safety by failing to review safety procedures after the merger of LNOX on 1 October 2014 and failing to announce and appoint personnel assuming the safety portfolio after the Accused’s resignation. The duration of offending was on or before 12 October 2015. After the merger, he failed to review LNOX’s safety procedures and focused more on LNOX’s business and finances. Mr Tham was sentenced to a fine of $45,000, in default two months’ imprisonment.

> (b)      _Public Prosecutor v Tan Chee Boon_ (DSC-900898-2017) (“_Tan Chee Boon_”): The offender was the managing director of a company in the business of fish hatcheries and fish farms. His duties were to manage the finances, administration, planning and operations. He pleaded guilty to a charge under s 12(1) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA for failing to ensure that there was a risk assessment conducted for the works conducted by employees, that there were adequate safe work procedures established, and that procedures for dealing with emergencies were implemented. One of the company’s workers dived into water to retrieve an oxygen cylinder that had fallen into the sea. Although the worker tied a nylon rope around his waist as an emergency line, the line unknotted. The worker was last seen on the seabed with his left arm pinned down by the oxygen cylinder. SCDF divers were unable to find the worker’s body and only recovered the oxygen cylinder. The offender was sentenced to a fine of $40,000, in default six weeks’ imprisonment.

> (c)      _Public Prosecutor v Teo Wee Kiat_ (DSC-900518-2016) (“_Teo Wee Kiat_”): The offender was the Director of Control Operations at SMRT Trains Ltd. His duties included managing and approving all requests for access to train tracks. He pleaded guilty to a charge under s 12(1) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA for failing to ensure that SMRT Train Ltd’s employees comply with approved operating procedures when accessing the train track during traffic hours and failing to ensure that procedures actually practised passed safety audits and were documented and disseminated. A group of employees were deployed to inspect a fault on a train track. The deceased employees were trainees following the inspection team. Owing to non-compliance with safety procedures, they were hit by an incoming train and died. The offender was sentenced to a fine of $55,000, in default five weeks’ imprisonment.

> (d)      _Public Prosecutor v Hee Kok Hwa_ (DSC-900273-2021) (“_Hee Kok Hwa_”): The offender was the director of a food catering company. He pleaded guilty to a charge under s 11(_c_) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA for failing to take reasonably practicable measures to ensure that the machinery kept on the workplace is safe and without risks to every person. The company premises were equipped with a cargo hoist consisting of a metal cage that travelled between the first and mezzanine levels. The deceased and her colleague were inside the metal cage when it became stuck between levels. Her colleague stomped on the hoist platform, causing the platform to descend suddenly. The deceased lost her balance and fell towards the opening of the hoist. Her head was caught between the top frame of the cage and the hoist’s landing on the mezzanine level. Investigations revealed that the company failed to properly maintain the cargo hoist and failed to ensure that it was operated by trained personnel only. Although the offender was physically present on most days during the offending period and aware that the hoist was used to transfer materials, he did not take steps to ascertain if it was safe for use and did not implement necessary measures to ensure that the hoist was only operated by trained personnel. He was sentenced to a fine of $45,000, in default three months’ imprisonment.

> (e)      _Public Prosecutor v Yang Han Guo_ (DSC-900397-2018) (“_Yang Han Guo_”): The offender was the project manager and authorised representative of the company who was in charge of safety matters, including risk assessments. He pleaded guilty to a charge under s 12(2) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA for failing to take reasonably practicable measures to ensure the safety and health of persons (not being employees) who may be affected by any undertaking carried on in the workplace. A company employee who was operating the forklift collided into a worker who was patching holes in the area. The offender was aware of the deficiencies in risk management and the possibility of a collision between a forklift and a ground worker. Nonetheless, he failed to ensure that the company established and implemented a traffic management plan on the viaduct and other control measures. He was sentenced to a fine of $48,000, in default two months’ imprisonment.

61     I considered the list of offenders and fines that the Defence submitted to be of limited assistance. Apart from the designation of the offenders, the date of their sentences and the fines imposed, there were no other details provided on the facts and circumstances of each case to serve as a basis for comparison with the present case.

62     Among the sentencing precedents cited by the Prosecution, I noted that only _Tan Chee Boon, Teo Wee Kiat_ and _Steven Tham_ concerned the offence under s 12(1) read with s 48(1) of the WSHA. My assessment of how the present case compared to these precedents was as follows:

> (a)     The present case was more egregious than _Tan Chee Boon_. There were twice as many failures involved. Moreover, given the nature of work involving gas analysis and testing, there was a higher level of potential harm in the present case than in _Tan Chee Boon_.

> (b)     The present case was less egregious than _Teo Wee Kiat_. The offender in that case, being the person responsible for approving train track access, had more direct control than the Accused who had management oversight but was not involved in the day-to-day operations of the laboratory.

> (c)     The most relevant precedent was _Steven Tham_. While the Defence relied on the EHS Structure and the EHS Manual that stated that Mr Tham was ultimately responsible for safety matters, it did not follow that the Accused was less culpable than Mr Tham concerning safety issues relating to the laboratory. The fact remained that the Accused had management oversight of the laboratory generally. Mr Tham was responsible for the overall operations of LNOX, including safety matters. In my view, they had similar levels of oversight, albeit over different areas of responsibility. I was not satisfied that there was clear basis for stating that either was more culpable than the other.

#### Parity in sentence

63     In _Public Prosecutor v Ng Sae Kiat and other appeals_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 5 SLR 167</span>, the High Court held that the parity principle was applicable for sentencing offenders who did not participate in the same act constituting the offence but who, as a matter of substance, were participants in a common criminal enterprise (at \[78\]).

64     Notwithstanding the slight differences in the duration of offending and failures specified in the charge (see \[60(a)\] above), I was of the view that the Accused and Mr Tham could be said to be involved in similar offences or a “common criminal enterprise”. Accordingly, the principle of parity was relevant.

#### Conclusion

65     For the reasons stated above, and having regard to the principle of parity and Mr Tham’s sentence, I sentenced the Accused to a fine of $45,000 (in default two months' imprisonment).
